    <exercise workspace="3in">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Use the ideas from the last problem to find the formula for an exponential function that passes through the points <m>(7,4)</m> and <m>(15,2)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

</page>
<page>
<exercise workspace="4in">
    
<statement>
<p>
    Once you can find a formula for an exponential function that looks like
    <me>
        f(t) = a\cdot b^{\frac{t-h}{P}}
    </me>
    recall that you can always replace <m>b</m> with <m>e^{k}</m> where <m>k = \ln(b)</m>. Thus,
    <me >
        f(t) = a e^{{\frac{k(t-h)}{P}}}.
    </me>
    Describe the transformations done to the parent function <m>y=e^t</m> to obtain the function <m>f(t)</m> given above.
</p>
</statement>
</exercise>

</page>

<exercise workspace="6in">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Now that we can build our functions in the form <m>f(t) = a e^{{\frac{k(t-h)}{P}}}</m> we can model and solve for inputs easily.
        </p>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>P</m> is a population of an ant colony in your professor's backyard. One week after they noticed the colony, there were <m>250</m> ants. Two weeks later, there we <m>375</m>. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find formulas for the population of ants both in the form <m>P = a\cdot b^{\frac{t-h}{P}}</m> and <m>a\cdot e^{\frac{k(t-h)}{P}}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                How long after the colony was first noticed will there be <m>1000</m> ants?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
</exercise>

